Redwine by David Havera

I will be evaluating a red wine quality dataset. This dataset contains over 1,599 red wines with 11 features consisting of the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the wine on a scale from 0 (bad) to 10 (excellent). I will be analyzing this data set to determine what chemical properties influence the quality of red wine.

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 13 variables with 1,399 observations. All variables are numeric with the exception of X and quality being integers. There are no #N/As in the data set.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I used the ggpair to show relationships across all the variables.
I ran 3 charts in order to make the data readable. Each chart compares each variable against quality readable. Based on this analysis, I decided on the following features of interest: alcohol, volatile acidity, and sulphates.

Alcohol The ggpair shows that alcohol has a positive correlation to quality of 0.48 and over 75% of the wines have at least 9.5% alcohol. It appears anything above 14 would be an outlier.

Sulphates Sulphates have a .25 correlation to quality and over 75% of the wines have at least a .55 level of sulphates. It appears anything above 1.2 and below 0.25 would be an outlier.

Voliatile acidity Volatile acidity has a (.39) correlation to quality and over 75% of the wines have at least a .39 level of acidity. It appears anything above 1.2 and below 0.2 would be an outlier.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
Wine quality is a blend of all of these features and I believe that they all

play a role in wine quality.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

I chose the variables with the higest correlation to quality: alcohol, volatile.acidity, and sulphates. I ran the R2 for these features against quality and came up with a total R2 of 0.44, which means that 44% of quality can be explained by these variables.
Sulphates looks particularly low at only 6%.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I found it interesting that fixed acidity had a correlation of 0.67 
to citric acid.  There seems to be a lot of features related to acid in the 
dataset.  If I am not able to accurately predict from the three features that 
I chose, then I will look into engineering another feature around acidity that 
combines citric acid.


### What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship was 0.48 correlation of quality to alcohol.  I expect that this is the most impactful feature to predict the quality of wine, but we will later test this hypothesis.

# Multivariate Plots Section

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Density has a strong negative correlation to alcohol of (0.5) and a positive correlation of 0.36 to residual sugars. This makes sense since the data set description of this feature says that density is dependent on alcohol levels and sugars. However, its interesting to see the relationship in terms of correlation numbers.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Earlier I could have said that residual sugars is a throw away variable because it has only 0.0137 correlation to quality. However, residual sugar can impact density which can negativitly impact alcohol which can impact wine quality. I wonder if PCA would condense residual sugars, density, and alcohol together.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

I chose the random forest (RF) to evaluate the dataset.

Strengths of RF: + Limited parameter tuning default parameters often have great performance + Fast + Versitile + Great for feature selection because it evaluates a lot of decision tree variations + Illustrates information gain by inclusion/exclusion of variables in the forest

Limitations of RF: + Poor Peformance: small data sets + Fragmentation Problem: each split has diminishing information gain + Prone to overfitting

Description One

The correlation map is a great visual to show why we initially chose alcohol, volatile.acidity, and sulphates as the main features to explore. It also highlights the relationships we observed between other features such as density and residual sugars and alcohol.

Description Two

The random forest classifer is a powerful tool to predict the quality of wine.

Plot Three

Description Three

I chose the boxplot above because I wanted to illustrate the million dollar question:

Is the model able to predict the quality of wine. The graph illustrates that the answer is yes.

In fact, the overall performance of the random forest classifier was excellent.
It had a mean accuracy of around 80% on quality of 5 and increased steadily to a mean accuracy of 86% for quality of 8.

Reflection

Overall, I analyzed the data and built a model that could correclty predict the wine quality with a high accuracy based on alcohol content, sulphates, and volatile acidity.

I do believe that accuracy can be further improved because these 3 features only explained 35% of the variance, so the model could benefit from PCA or Kbestfeature selection. In fact, feature selection and feature engineering are areas that I struggled with. I wanted to discover a relationship with the acid features, but I failed to find anything meaningful.

However, I am happy to have successfully built a base level starting point upon which more indepth analysis can be performed.
